        "id": 4725805
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-23T23:53:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is a good suggestion. It makes sense architecturally because these values define the capacity of the solver\u0027s internal buffers rather than a property of the cost function itself.\n\nMy main concern is maintaining backward compatibility for existing clients of `TinySolver`. Currently, the template signature is:\n\n```cpp\ntemplate \u003ctypename Function, typename LinearSolver \u003d ...\u003e\nclass TinySolver;\n```\n\nIf we add `MAX_NUM_RESIDUALS` and `MAX_NUM_PARAMETERS` as template arguments, we face two issues:\n\n* Breaking API: If we place them before `LinearSolver`, we break any code that explicitly provides a custom solver.\n\n* Dependency: The default `LinearSolver` (typically `Eigen::LDLT`) depends on the matrix size. If we place the new parameters at the end, the default solver cannot easily reference them without more complex template metaprogramming.\n\nBecause of this, I opted to pull these values from the `Function` class as optional traits. This allows us to support variable sizes while keeping the `TinySolver` API completely unchanged for all existing users.\n\nDo you have a preferred template structure in mind that would move these to TinySolver while preserving the existing LinearSolver parameter?",
      "parentUuid": "4ae2c55f_ebe0c0b4",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 154,
        "startChar": 10,
        "endLine": 154,
        "endChar": 18
      },
      "revId": "5de45156fa7fbad475cf0f26f01f00501fe200b7",
      "serverId": "cdcfcfbe-2044-3b1f-b5d4-da77ad542329"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f4504981_e8b2ca5e",
        "filename": "include/ceres/tiny_solver.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 154,
      "author": {
        "id": 5002
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-24T00:12:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The ideal thing would be if we can do the right thing where we make these optional parameters the last two parameters, and do whatever metaprogramming thats needed. How complicated is that going to be?\n\nmaybe instead of code churn here we can iterate over a simpler prototype?\n\nactually now that I think about it some more, why do we need the linear solver to be a template parameter, I suppose if we are planning on doing something like change linear solvers, \n\nbut in terms of dense solvers, there are only three choices,\n\nLLT\nLDLT\nQR\n\nQR is not going to happen (our code will have to evolve way too much for that), the only choices are LLT or LDLT, so I think the only question is how do we keep the ability to switch between them without needing the full template specialization, and that way your ordering problem becomes simpler.",
      "parentUuid": "59f286e6_f02aae95",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 154,
        "startChar": 10,
        "endLine": 154,
        "endChar": 18
      },
      "revId": "5de45156fa7fbad475cf0f26f01f00501fe200b7",
